<subSubSection id="53437724ABA902BE4918EE67205ECAA4" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="822C92204CB71673A33332E790C936F9" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="35324F8305DC8A7B1AF6623540F5014D" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
This is distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="6EB2BA18C66BE83E364509963585D6BC" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis id="39FB8ABDE893791405E92476C0E7E61C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the shorter corolla (1.5-2.5 cm long), which is uniformly pink. The sepals are usually narrowly (not broadly) ovate, but this character is not constant. It is essentially a large-flowered form of 
<taxonomicName id="13B06F144C8F14FCFA2139EF3D43FA7E" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="triloba">
<emphasis id="E9E6EEA46CC19428AE28413D6E66E496" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. triloba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and has the appearance of being an intermediate with 
<taxonomicName id="DC9F2A035668BB9A51C3F7FA3E102382" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis id="ED55D5167FFC7AD7E434C95848036A79" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
